 mock epitaph.It balances discussion of canonical figures such as Ben Jonson and Sir John Harington with a wide range of lesser known poets, drawing on both manuscript and print sources.In its breadth The epigram in England serves as a foundational introduction to the genre for students, and through its detailed case studies it offers rich analysis for advanced scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEpigrams, EnglishxHistory and criticismxEarly modern, 1500-1700. 0aEpigrams, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBen Jonson.  aEpigrams.  aEpitaphs.  aHenry Parrot.  aManuscript poetry.  aNeo-Latin verse.  aSir John Harington.  aThomas Bastard.  aThomas Freeman.1 aDoelman, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499758840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997588/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles